dern<br />distributions (and not-so-modern ones, for that matter) are compiled<br />with i686 support, so gcc just generates fucomip directly. So it's<br />just "plain FPU" code (no mmx, nothing like that), but it still fails.<br /><br />The "set regular integer flags instructions" versions of floating<br />point compares are some of the bigger improvements to the legacy i87<br />instruction set, because the sequences to do FP compares without them<br />are just insane. I forget the details, but it's something like "store<br />status word to ax, then use sahf to get it into the flags register".<br />Crazy crazy crap. So it's no wonder that gcc wants to use a i686-only<br />instruction even for just regular FP code if at all possible.<br /><br />I suspect it shouldn't be that hard to add f[u]compi[p] support to the<br />emulator.<br /><br />But I also expect that most modern distributions are likely fairly<br />eager to use mmx etc, which sounds like a major pain to emulate.<br /><br />                Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
